Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @sweet potato{1} into small 1cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop them onto a
large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then
toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced chicken breast{260%g}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}
and stir-fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

While the chicken cooks, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated)
(or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed, then thinly slice half the chilli.
Finely chop the rest.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}.

Once the chicken has browned, stir in the garlic, @ginger puree{15%g}, finely
chopped chilli (careful, it's hot - add less if you'd prefer things milder) and
@tomato puree{30%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @water{150%ml}(for the sauce) and
@chicken stock paste{10%g}, then stir together.

Bring the stew to the boil and simmer until the sauce has thickened,
~{5-6%minutes}.

Once thickened, stir in the @baby spinach{40%g} a handful at a time until wilted
and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Remove from the heat, then squeeze in some lime juice and add the @soy sauce{15%ml}.
Taste and add more lime juice if needed.

Stir in the roasted sweet potato and add a splash of water if it's a little too
thick.

Spoon the chicken stew into your #bowls{}.

Top with the sliced chilli (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and lime
zest to finish.

Enjoy!